\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid6648419 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Professor Peter Townsend
\par Summary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 30 June 1997
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 [Born 1928] Mother lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}
 with grandmother. Grandmother the key figure in his early life; she was separated from grandfather, and to earn money she took in washing, rented out two upstairs rooms, and acted as midwife's helper. Grandfather's family were fisherfolk from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}County{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Durham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. His mother was a singer, originally in local opera and operetta; recently he received an honorary doctorate in the former {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town Hall{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, on the platform from which his mother had 
once performed the lead role in Madam Butterfly. She met Peter's father in the Stockton Amateur Dramatics Society where they sang together. He got a job in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} around when Peter was born. Peter's mother then left her father and returned to live with his grandmother in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}, when Peter was about one and a half.
\par 
\par Later they all moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, where his mother earned from singing in clubs and Masonic Lodges. She played an important role in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Girl in a Taxi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 . She shifted from opera to comedienne work. Soon after the outbreak of war she hit moderate fame in a musical, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 New Faces}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
. Then she toured entertaining troops, and reached her peak with two Royal Command Performances at the end of the war. After that, in her forties, she
 stopped getting new commissions, and after a tragic period of depression got a job with Shell, first as a clerk, then as a supervisor. Did not remarry, although had another partner for a while. Final years shut up at home. But an enormous influence on Pe
ter with her huge sense of narrative and wit.
\par 
\par Grandmother the more stable influence. She cooked and looked after the house while his mother went to work.
\par 
\par Father had flown for the Royal Flying Corps in the First World War, pretending he was older than he was. He regarded that as the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}high point{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 of his life. With the RAF again in the Second World War as a training pilot, including in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Peter saw virtually nothing of him as a child, and then, after his own marriage, very little. Blames himself partly for that. In the last dozen years of his life - he lived to 90 - got to know him much better, and became very fond of each other. 
\par 
\par Remembers his father visiting him in 1939 in a Blackpool guesthouse, where there were also refugees from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Liverpool{\*\xmlclose}
 slums. Peter's family respectable working class or lower middle class, so this was his first experience of a confrontation between respectables and roughs. His father very formal, accepted his mother's disapproval of visits, conveyed t
hrough a lawyer. He was a commercial traveller working on short-term contracts in the north of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, with a car. Gave only irregular maintenance. Finally divorced, and married his new partner Maisie in 1961. Had no other children.
\par 
\par Reflecting on the position of being an only child has led in part to Peter's keen interest in kinship and family relations.
\par 
\par Lived in flats in Pimlico, and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Belsize{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. Elementary schools in Pimlico and Hampstead. Influence of teacher, Miss Sard. Scholarship to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Street games. Games at home; lead toys. Boxing. Writing as a boy, and duplicating, a school magazine called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Bombshell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
. Playing cricket alone in the garden.
\par 
\par Grandmother had two other children besides Peter's mother. One son died of diphtheria at seven; this was the greatest blow of her life. The other son Bill was severely wounded in the Second World War, losing both legs; in hospital he met a nurse fif
teen years older, who married him and looked after him. They lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Portsmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, where he was an office worker with the Royal Navy. They had one son. Saw them once or twice a year.
\par 
\par Peter moved to Pimlico when aged four, because his mother saw {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as the only place where she could earn a living on the stage. At seven moved to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}Belsize Crescent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, attic flat; at 12 to a garden flat also there.
\par 
\par Summers following his mother singing at seaside resorts: Blackpool, Worthing, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Hastings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Llandudno.
\par 
\par Peter was playing on the beach, his grandmother in a deckchair. Even played cricket once for Arthur Askey's XI. Great fun. Mother did not sing much at home.
\par 
\par Hiding under the bed from air raids. Air Raid Warden aged 13.
\par 
\par National Service. Wrote love letters for illiterate Geordies. Accounts of the other {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 which he wrote in university weekly newspaper. Sees this interest as partly from experiences in childhood of people from different class backgrounds.
\par 
\par Isolation as only child led to much reading. Wodehouse, Crompton. Also writing: poetry, and school magazine. Becoming aware of the importance of style in putting ideas across.
\par 
\par Moral values, two big influences. Grandmother, true as a bell; always worked hard; lived to 97, last years with Peter in the 1960s, still crocheting; very dependable.
\par 
\par The other influence Cecil S. Walton, headmaster of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} all through the war. Opened experience. Devised `co
mmando exams' which combined cross-country running and swimming with writing exam papers. Peter did well at that. Discussed how to change the school with prefects in away-day. Was probably gay; committed suicide after an incident.
\par 
\par Peter was two years Captain of the school. He abolished the Cadet Corps. Set up charitable activities instead, for example for the blind. 
\par 
\par Peter had come as one of only four scholarship boys. Encouraged to apply for scholarships by Miss Sard, teacher at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}Fleet Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} s
chool. Neither mother nor grandmother had been very interested in his education. Grandmother left school at 11, as the eldest of thirteen, to look after the others. Mother left at 14. She was clever enough, but did not have a later chance - unlike Peter's
 first wife Ruth, who in her forties went back into education, got a law degree and became a barrister.
\par 
\par At school it was difficult for scholarship boys from a poorer background, but Peter adapted and made good friends. Often with minority groups, Catholics or Jews. 
\par 
\par Religion not important to him in childhood. However, through influence of Cecil Walton started attending {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}St Peter's Belsize Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and at 16 became a committed Christian, ardent and prudish. Then became interested in Christian Sci
ence through the influence of Ruth (with whom in love at 17) and her sister Jennifer. But Jennifer developed TB, just at the time when penicillin had been developed in 1947, but she and her family refused to take it and allowed her to die. That finished C
hristian Science for Peter, and led him to be more critical of other religions. His religious phase lasted only three or four years; from 15 or 16 to 18 or 19.
\par 
\par Wide range of activities at school, including designing posters; took Higher School Certificate 
in Art. (Peter later discovered that his father had been at a College of Further Education in Art, and was a good illustrator; he was in the same class as Henry Moore at Leeds, and thought very poorly of him!) Captain of school cricket, played tennis for 
the school and for Middlesex Second. 
\par 
\par Also very sociable. Friends included Tony Wagstaff, rugger player; and Cyril Shaldon, also rugger player and later his best man, who became a consultant general physician and moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Devon{\*\xmlclose}
; lost touch with both l
ater on. Also Alan Bowness, who introduced Peter to socialism, and was also interested in art and the cinematograph; he was a pacifist and did military service with the Quakers. Peter shocked family by putting up a Labour poster in 1945. Alan was later Di
rector of the Tate and married a daughter of Barbara Hepworth. They didn't remain close friends. 
\par 
\par Subjects at school, in addition to art, showed early talent in maths. Later was especially keen on English, writing stories and poetry. Also did well in geography, and was offered a scholarship in this subject to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But changed his mind after reading philosophy during his military service, and decided to read Moral Sciences instead. Under the post-war arrangement could have completed his degree
 in this in two years, but decided to stay on for a third year in order to read Social Anthropology for Part II. 
\par 
\par Went into the school Sixth Form early and stayed in it for three years. Left in June 1946 when just 18. Pleasure of summer farms, helping to bring in the harvest. July to November teaching in a private school in Kensington. 
\par 
\par Royal Army Education Corps, at Yeovil, and then Blandford Dorset. Turned down the chance of an officers' training course, fearing this might hold up going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Bitter winter of 1947, going to bed in clothes, ice on floor of hut. Then {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. The army was an important negative experience. Class system operating through army. But in retrospect, appreciates the professional skills of army discipline more. 
\par 
\par Peter has a love-hate relationship with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Best research university in the world. Beauty of the place. But separation from the other 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and the working class. Still has his notebooks from lectures and books. Inspir
ing people included Bertie Russell, who lectured weekly as an Emeritus. Visit from him and scoop for university paper about his views on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. John Wisdom also an influence. Poor lecturers included ultra-shy C. D. Broad, for divinity. For anthropology, learnt from Fortune, and J. C. Trevor (on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Caribbean{\*\xmlclose}), and Professor Meyer Fortes. 

\par 
\par Impressed by the anthropological method of living in a society and direct 
observation in contrast to sending out juniors and looking at data through a microscope in your study. Still believes that you need to be both a specialist and a generalist, because the two feed on each other. Today talks about this in contexts varying fr
om general practice to international development. You need to understand some of the cogs as well as the machine.
\par 
\par He wrote an article on the shopping areas for the university paper. Got to know a slum area because for three years after his first year he and Ruth lived in a cottage there in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}Clement Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. One up and one down. Playing with the children from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}Park Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} on Jesus Green. 
\par 
\par Serious illness in his second year, in Addenbrookes hospital, suspected meningitis and then polio,
 two lumbar punctures, very painful. Walton had said that if anything cut you down you should try to get back into the same sort of action as before as quickly as possible. At school, after an accident playing cricket when he lost three teeth he had playe
d for the school team again the same week. This time went as quickly as possible back to playing rugby.
\par 
\par However, now concentrated on journalism, and became editor of the university newsletter. Thought he was going to be a journalist until he discovered social anthropology. 
\par 
\par Ruth came up to live in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 from the start, and they married in 1949. She did some clerical work. Also worked with Peter on articles for the university newspaper. Edited the Varsity Handbook together. 
\par 
\par Her father a leadi
ng dentist, and President of the British Dental Association, knighted. Peter was very much the scholarship boy made good from down the hill. Met through a snowball fight on Hampstead Heath. Her parents had a beautiful house; remembers watching 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Wimbledon{\*\xmlclose} on television together in her Queen Anne drawing room.
\par 
\par {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} friends included Jack Ashley, later deaf MP, who was President of the Students' Union, a close friend.
\par 
\par Went to the Youth Festival in East Berlin in 1951 and through that learned of scholarships to the newly-set up Free University in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Berlin{\*\xmlclose}
. Went with Ruth and lived in student accommodation at Dahlem in late 1951; difficulty of getting enough food in the period after the airlift, living off mashed lungs. Came back for Ruth to have first child, Matthew, in February 1952.
\par 
\par Peter appointed to a low-paid Research Assistantship in Political and Economic Planning starting late in 1952. At first he commuted from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 but then they bought the tail end of the lease of a terraced cottage in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Hampstead, and then eventually later the freehold in 1953. Second son, Adam, born in local Nursing Home near there. 
\par 
\par At PEP worked with an unimaginative director, Ray Goodman. It was difficult to produ
ce radical and original work, because of the need to please both left and right wing; the board included both a Labour MP and a Conservative MP, Angus Maude. This was an important early experience of the need to fight against the bureaucratisation of soci
al science. 
\par 
\par First PEP pamphlet he did was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Poverty: Ten Years After Beveridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
, in 1952. The second, a very important experience, was a study of unemployment in the cotton industry, for which he visited Lancashire, talking to people queuing in Unemployment Exchanges: Rochdale, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oldham
{\*\xmlclose} and Colne. Remembers the early morning sound of clogs, and the drudgery of the machine work in the factories. Seventy hours a week then common. 
\par 
\par The poverty pamphlet was based on secondary evidence, but it was his idea to 
look at the poverty line. He wanted to see how the new welfare state was working. Looked at the successive studies by Booth and Rowntree and concluded that Rowntree's last work with Lavers, which had been very much welcomed by the Labour Government, was o
v
er-optimistic. The PEP Board were highly sceptical and so organised a debate with Lavers, which however Peter convincingly won. The improvements were mainly due to the return of full employment, rather than to progressive taxation or higher benefits. This
 led to a special meeting of the British Sociological Association, at which papers were given by Peter, Brian Abel-Smith and Dorothy Wedderburn. From then onwards, poverty was recognised to be a continuing problem.
\par 
\par Brian had begun working on poverty separately. He had also been at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but a little earlier, and they hadn't had much contact. Brian then worked at the National Institute for Economic and Social Research which was quite close to PEP. They began to meet and that sparked off a lifel
ong friendship. Brian wrote a Fabian pamphlet on social security, and then in 1955-7 they wrote a joint pamphlet on pensions, which to some extent foreshadowed Crossman's reforms. Peter had already written a PEP pamphlet on pensions which briefly suggeste
d an earnings-related pension on top of the flat rate basic pension. 
\par 
\par They also worked on this with the help of Richard Titmuss, whose judgement they greatly respected at the time. By this time Peter had gone on to work with Michael Young at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Institute{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Community Studies{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, from 1954 to 1957. But Peter, finding himself frustrated because Michael was always jumping on from one thing to the next, then decided to throw in his lot with Titmuss at LSE.
\par 
\par Influence in his social 
research of anthropology. He drew partly on his own unusual family background. Classic studies of Margaret Mead, Meyer Fortes, Radcliffe Brown, all about non-western societies. He wanted to indentify the peculiarities of our own life.
\par 
\par Importance of the functionalist idea, that societies are systematic. Has kept this idea all his life. Talcott Parsons was dull but had a point. Individuals matter but they operate from a structured position. Is against both determinism and the idea of com
plete individual freedom. The idea of the structural situation is very exciting. 
\par 
\par Developed this at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Institute{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Community Studies{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at Bethnal Green through looking at the extended family, and finding the importance not o
nly of grandparents but also of great-grandparents, and connections, needs and obligations well beyond that. Some relationships were even tribal.
\par 
\par At the Institute originally he was going to research on the elderly, Michael Young on the middle-aged, and Peter Willmott on young children, but soon Willmott and Young joined together to write }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Family and Kinship in East London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 .
\par 
\par For old people, Peter decided not to sample through houses, but through GPs' cards. Found extraordinary contrasts in family life. At on
e extreme the Agombars, who had nine or ten surviving sons and daughters living locally, and lived in Club Row, keeping an aviary of birds, with always between two or six of the family with them visiting, drinking tea and eating bread pudding. Got to know
 them well. It was like meeting a tribe, who had between 80 and 100 relatives in the vicinity. Also collected photographs of those who had emigrated to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}America
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Once took a photograph of two busloads of relatives, about 100 of them. He felt like an anthropologist photographing a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}village{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName
}}Indians{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Latin America{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par At the other extreme a single woman who was the only daughter of an only child, whose mother had died 30 years ago, and had never known her father, who s
eemed to have no relatives at all. She lived in a single room in industrial dwellings. She occasionally spoke to a neighbour on the landing, or went to the local library to look at a newspaper. Once Peter took her a present on Christmas Eve and the only s
ign of Christmas in her room was a piece of Woolworths wrapping paper stuck over the mantelpiece.
\par 
\par Discovered Katherine Dwellings, industrial dwellings where Beatrice Potter (Webb) had worked as a visitor and rent collector. At LSE he found her diary of thi
s work in 1886, and of her successor Ella Pyecroft for two years later. Visited all the current occupants. These included other isolates, such as ex-convicts, or a seaman from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Rio de Janeiro{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Also ex-prostitutes. But also networks of relatives, who could bring joint pressure, for example to complain about the caretaker or the landlord. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Katherine{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Buildings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was a formative experience.
\par 
\par Since then, structural changes have made extended families living close together less common. But more visiting by car, and even frequent exchanges of visits with sisters who have been 30 years in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Believes in the need to combine structural analysis with microstudy. And you should study more than one 
generation, because societies have a history. You also need to look at the evolution of laws. Read poetry, read fiction, talk with politicians. Participant observation, and talking informally to people, is essential for grasping how people see priorities.
 One method cannot give all the answers. The more you can use others, the better. 
\par 
\par Went to the funeral of a brother of the Agombars, an extraordinary experience.
\par 
\par Need to complement the questionnaire with other methods. Of the 200 old people, he interviewe
d 160 himself and Peter Marris interviewed 40. This was Peter's first major experience of direct research. Deliberately did not precode too much, in order to allow space for people's own words. Afterwards, immediately wrote up the interview thematically. 
Because if you have a complete typescript of a recording it is impossible to find what you need. Cut up thematic pieces in envelopes for different chapters.
\par 
\par Got ten old people to keep a diary for a week. Some were semi-literate and could write very little.
 Did not keep a fieldwork diary himself. Occasionally wrote down notes of what happened to him on some days in the 1950s-60s, but less than 4% of his time. Describes interviewing approach: explains simply and clearly what he is doing. No concealed microph
one. Wrote notes during the interview, but stopped if it seemed to be distracting the interviewee. Later that day would dictate a summary, including verbatim sections. Has a good short-term memory. 
\par 
\par Took some photographs, which he still has. But Routledge 
would not use them in the book. Show how street life was then: women standing outside their doors, leaning on their brushes, or scrubbing their steps; `little mothers' aged 12 or 13 pushing the pram, showing the baby off to their girlfriends. The pram was
 then a status symbol, often built in chrome.
\par 
\par He did have a tape recorder, which was then novel, and went back to some interviewees to record them. Only did it a few times. It has proved difficult to transfer them onto cassettes. Has about 20 recorded hour
s. This was subsequent to the main themes, because he realised that some of the interviewees could give information going back to the 1880s, and he wanted to look at change over the generations. It was a kind of oral history.
\par 
\par Recordings can create far too
 much information, with a terrible problem of selection. He still believes that even if you record, it is best to go back home and take another half an hour summarising the main points. This can then be the basis of later selection. 
\par 
\par Wanted to use people's own words. Decided that rather than having many short quotes it was better to have longer ones and to introduce the speaker. Has been criticised for choosing biased examples to quote. But people also choose what statistics to quote 
to back their arguments. He believes it is better to quote the extremes, rather than Mr Grey in the middle.
\par 
\par Peter left PEP because it was too bureaucratic and limited in its ambitions, and he wanted to do major research. It was set up in the 1930s, and iss
ued some influential reports in the 1940s, for example on trade unions and on the need for a public health service. Harold Nicolson was one of its sponsors. It later became the Policy Studies Institute. At that this time these independent research organis
ations were an innovative British feature; visiting Americans were very jealous. 
\par 
\par He met Michael Young while at PEP, who was working on the Labour Party manifesto, but had many other creative ideas - including that for the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Institute{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Community Studies{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Peter was involved from the early days and got a grant from the Nuffield Foundation for his study of old people.

\par 
\par Disagreed with Michael about how to write up his research: Michael wanted a more journalese approach than Peter
. Peter got his way, although now thinks that Michael may have been right. It also turned out that the major purpose of the Institute was not to research the extended family. So Peter decided instead to work with Richard Titmuss at LSE. Brian Abel-Smith w
as already there, and they were working together on pensions. Peter took up a post as research fellow cum lecturer, and raised a further grant from the Nuffield Foundation for his book on old people's homes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
\par The Institute was in a Georgian house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}Victoria Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, close to the Universities Settlement - it had earlier been at another settlement, Oxford House. Used to lunch at the settlement, and also visited another regularly, Mary Ward House. Spent 1954-7 interviewing in thos
e surrounding streets; and also in Greenford. Finished the book in two years. In his last year, worked on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Katherine{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Buildings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} but never wrote this up; even met three people who were alive in Beatrice Webb's time. 
\par 
\par Michael was away a lot. The closest collaboration was between Peter Willmott, Peter Marris and himself. Peter Marris has read philosophy at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. He went on to be a District Officer in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kenya{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Debated then about the transition to independence. He wrote a novel on 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Japan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Peter had a high opinion of him: articulate and sensitive. Went on to write his book on widows, which was extraordinarily good. Stayed on at the Institute, and wrote books also on higher education, and about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa
{\*\xmlclose}. A fine writer: recent book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Loss and Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
. Has seen little of him in recent years, is in the States; but met last year.
\par 
\par The Institute was participative, but Michael didn't like it when things did not go his way. He was a vulnerable
, insecure person, often ill. But he knew how to get new ideas launched. Involved Ed Shils in the Institute. Michael himself went as a sociologist to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} but didn't like it. He was always trying out new careers, every two or three years. He was already running the Consumer Association before Peter left the Institute in 1957. Peter Willmott and Peter T often left holding the baby.
\par 
\par Michael wanted books to tell an unvarnished story, powerful and rounded. Peter more inclined to put in exceptions
. For example, although he admired the strength of working class culture, there were oppressive aspects of the family life, such as male domination, although they were less sensitive to this than we are today.
\par 
\par He was very friendly with Michael, who was so
me 15 years older, sharing common enthusiasms and interest in the family. Michael was less interested in income distribution. But Peter was closer to Peter Marris, and to a lesser extent to Peter Willmott. Michael was elusive, often ill, very much mixed u
p with Dartington, and his uncertainty created uncertainty in others. \lquote We had to keep him on line. We were the ballast in his life at that time\rquote .
\par 
\par Regrets that Michael did not build on the early success of the Institute. Good on public relations. Less democratic. Took actions and then tried to convince you afterwards. But could bounce back: indestructible as well as vulnerable.
\par 
\par Michael depended heavily on Peter Willmott for producing the material he need to write, but Peter W depended on Michael for ideas a
nd direction. Peter W less creative than Peter Marris, but a friendly person, who did eventually acquire authority for his work in housing. And he had a special quality in the group in being from a working class background and having worked as a Labour Pa
rty organiser.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 13 October 1997}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
\par 
\par Mixture of social classes he met in National Service; new interests included poetry and politics. Also became interested in world government. In 1947 sent a piece on this to Maurice Edelman MP, who invited him to lunch at th
e House of Commons and was extraordinarily hospitable. Around 1961 was lecturing on social medicine at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and his daughter Natasha was one of the students in the audience. Peter's interests in inequalities 
in health came to a head in the 1970s when he was asked to lecture on this, leading to his participation in the Black Report, but goes back earlier. Probably due to Professor Gerry Morris who invited him to lecture at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 from around 1959. United Nations was an inspirational cause at that time.
\par 
\par Had just decided to go to LSE. The Department of Social Science and Administration was beginning to bubble there. Sociology at LSE set in rather a narrow mould, saw so
cial policy as applied science, lacked a sufficiently dynamic view of social development. But it was the centre of British sociology at the time. David Glass among others becoming well-known. Social Science and Administration still more vital under Richar
d
 Titmuss. Early notable appointments included David Donnison and Brian Abel-Smith; later, Hilary Rose and Tessa Blackstone. Peter chose to go there as an apprentice to Titmuss. Came as a Research Fellow with his Nuffield money but also given a Lectureship
 so that he could teach. No proper interview for this. 
\par 
\par Had a group of ten or eleven students. Would set aside days for individual tutorials, an hour each. Doubts whether he is a good teacher. No training. Just needed to know the subject, and have somethin
g fresh to impart. Tutorials were part of the normal system at LSE. Key role of Kit Russell, who organised the student social work assignments. Value of giving the students small research exercises. Dissertation projects, some outstanding, involving much 
interviewing and fifty pages long. Peter helped to extended this project work at LSE with Kit Russell. 
\par 
\par One student project was on high rise flats. Found that they were very unsuitable for families with children. This was published as a pamphlet - at a time when the government were encouraging high rise building. 
\par 
\par Exchange of influence with teaching in schools. Helped to launch the Comprehensive Schools Committee. Exciting aspect of 1960s.
\par 
\par Richard Titmuss: first met 1953/4. Michael Young had secured him as chairman of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Institute{\*\xmlclose} of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Community Studies{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Labour Party commissio
ned report on pensions from Titmuss, Brian Abel-Smith and Peter and they worked together on this 1954-7. Wanted to work with him as an apprentice. Enormously impressive bearing. Perhaps less original mind than Brian.
\par 
\par Deliberate style of speech. Took over a room. Wise old man of the tribe. Thoughts often sharp and questioning. But in private, rather insecure. Sent out drafts for comment long in advance. Unprepossessing large house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Acton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, where his wife did everything for him. No specialised educ
ation. Left school early. No degree. Farmer's son who had become an insurance clerk; wrote some books in spare time, through which invited to become a war historian on social policy. That led to Chair at LSE. Wife protective; only one daughter, later on, 
so not exposed to challenging intimate influences. A bit insecure, so wanted support; lacked magnanimity towards those he thought disloyal.
\par 
\par Differences of opinion with Titmuss in late 1960s. Firstly, about Northern Ireland, where Peter had published a repo
rt accusing the Supplementary Benefits Commission - of which Titmuss was Deputy Chairman from 1967 - of colluding in discrimination against Catholics. Secondly, because Peter backed the student movement at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose}, while Titmuss opposed it at LSE.
\par 
\par Nevertheless an extraordinary influence. Notable book on the gift relationship and the commercialisation of blood. Greatly regrets that they did not patch things up before he died in 1972. More in common than differences.
\par 
\par Quite close, but not intimate. Titmus
s was quite isolated with his wife, both suffered and gained from that. Few saw him let his hair down. For Peter, a father figure. Disagreed more as time went on. For example, Titmuss could accept a mix of means-testing and universal benefits, while Peter
 was more strongly against means-testing. Also Titmuss inclined to the Liberal Party, Peter to Labour. He did not see the student protests of the 1960s as exciting catalysts of change, as Peter did. 
\par 
\par Difference between Titmuss and Head of Social Work at LSE. Partly a question of personalities. But those in social work had a narrower view, not looking critically at the structures within which they worked. You need to do both.
\par 
\par The most important things he gained from Titmuss were his support and fatherly advice; and his ability to turn over a question and look at it from different perspectives.
\par 
\par Brian Abel-Smith one of the half dozen most important social policy researchers of the century. More incisive and original than Titmuss, though few recognise this. Ha
s covered more ground with more high quality research than anyone else. Crucial early achievement was Guillebaud Report with Titmuss as a vindication of the National Health Service. Also published as a separate book. Unusual in introducing a historical di
mension, in both }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Hospitals}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The History of Nursing}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 . Thirdly, his rare understanding of the legal system in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Lawyers and the Courts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 .
\par 
\par Aristocratic background, but cut adrift from this. Became a socialist at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Winchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Had money: set up and ra
n a men's clothing shop, "Just Men", in his spare time. Close friend of Hugh Dalton. Very modern taste in his flat. Thought of becoming an MP, would have made a good Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer; decided not to risk it, because homosexual. Original 
financial thinking on pensions, and on health service. Twenty years treasurer of Fabian Society.
\par 
\par Brian would pretend in public that he might be marrying a biscuit heiress. Few knew he was homosexual. Peter did, from the start. Had an occasional social relationship with Brian's partner.
\par 
\par After Titmuss died, Brian was supportive: edited a collection of papers, and phoned his widow regularly. Gave her advice.
\par 
\par He was a garden designer, knowledgeable about plants. A very good cook. Did things without fuss. Self
-effacing. A facilitator for others: Titmuss, Crossman, Barbara Castle, David Ennals. Unusual as a political adviser in getting on well with senior civil servants. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8661181 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 His pressure for disability benefits in the 1970s was effective. He became essential to the World Health Organisation. Visits to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Indonesia{\*\xmlclose}, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Mauritius{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tanzania{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par The rift with Titmuss was also about Dennis Marsden's report on fatherless fami
lies, which again went against some of the precepts of the Supplementary Benefits Commission. Brian tried to keep friends with both sides, and withdrew from the poverty research team partly because of this conflict; although more because Crossman had aske
d him to join him as Principal Political Adviser, and Brain saw this as a chance to reform pensions policy. But Peter was thrown by his withdrawing: missed his economic expertise.
\par 
\par Hence Peter and Titmuss' paths diverged. Remained fond, but in 1970s-80s little contact. Renewed contact late 1980s, and thereafter occasional. But shocked when he died in 1996. Wrote obituary for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Independent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  - of a friend he loved. Now bitterly regrets the disagreement, and not winding things up properly.
\par 
\par Dorothy Cole, later Dorothy Cole-Wedderburn, another colleague of this period. Economics at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}; important early work on means-testing. Worked together on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Old People in Three Industrial Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  and on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Aged in the Welfare State}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 . Married Bill Wedderburn, a lawyer. She became VC of Queen Elizabeth's College.
\par 
\par Kit Russell: revered her. Now in her nineties, still lives in Cheyne Walk, where used to hold musical evenings. Her husband was one of the first male hospital almoners. Extraordinary with students, who conf
ided in her. Had her finger on everything: managed the whole programme and timetable, and was also an extraordinary therapist. But self-effacing and modest. A great facilitator. Still a friend.
\par 
\par Outlines development of research interests and programmes. First phase, PEP first six research papers: unemployment, pensions, education, costs of welfare - so an introduction to Welfare State issues. Second phase, at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Institute{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Community Studies{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, extended family: focuses on old people. 
\par 
\par Third stag
e, out of that, group of projects on ageing. Nursing Homes, with Carol Woodroffe; some funding from National Council for the Welfare of Old People. Biggest project 1957-61 on residential homes, funded by Nuffield Foundation. Followed by comparative study 
of US and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Denmark{\*\xmlclose}, with American funding, jointly with Dorothy Wedderburn. Also wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Aged in the Welfare State}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  with her, published 1965. Also worked on, but never published, study of old people in hospitals, with Sheila Benson, from 1964; also American funding.
\par 
\par Fourth stage, from 1967, projects on poverty. Beginning with Hilary Land on large families and Dennis Marsden on small families. Papers and unpublished work by John Veit-Wilson and Adrian Sinfield. Had intended a special piece of research o
n unemployment. Was writing up the poverty study already in 1972-3, but not published until 1979. 
\par 
\par Fifth stage, inequalities in health, began with a paper in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Lancet }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
in the early 1970s. Work on the Black Report 1976-9, published 1980. Subsequent and continuing research on this in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} and the north-east of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}England
{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Sixth stage the international dimension. From the 1970s, work on poverty in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Europe{\*\xmlclose}. Especially the 1990s, with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
The International Analysis of Poverty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 , and report for UNDP on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Georgia{\*\xmlclose} and other papers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 24 November 1997}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
\par 
\par In Bethnal Green got interested in homes for the elderly. In what situations did families use them? Visited two institutions. One was a former workhouse, Southern Grove; remembers the warden in his velvet 
dressing gown. His research showed that you were much less likely to end up in such an institution if you had close family and especially a daughter nearby. It was the single or childless who predominated. Need for a national housing policy which gives pr
iority to placing family members nearby. Peter wrote this up as a chapter for his Bethnal Green book.
\par 
\par Peter decided, against Michael Young's wishes, to do a further study of homes for the elderly. Got support from the Nuffield Foundation, and moved his research base to LSE. It was visiting the former workhouse which inspired him to do a national study.

\par 
\par It was the first national study of homes for the elderly, and used a new method of sampling institutions - a sampling method also used by others, such as Ro
yston Lambert in his research on boarding schools. They visited 180 homes, varying from enormous old institutions like Luxborough Lodge near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Baker St{\*\xmlclose}
 which housed 1100 people to small private homes for four or six registered patients. 
\par 
\par Four fifths of
 the interviewing was with Bob Pinker, later professor at LSE. In each area they would start by interviewing the Chief Welfare Officer: two-hour interview on policies, facts and figures. One of the few of them who became a friend was John Hanson in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South Shields{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Visiting homes. Typically, often a large house converted by Local Authority to a home, pleasant, but at the end of a long drive, so isolated. 30 to 80 beds, mostly women. Residents allowed few possessions. Run b
y staff rather like an army barracks, over-tidy. Lack of comforts like cushions, carpets, hot water bottles. Residents not encouraged to make tea for themselves or wash up or entertain in their own rooms. Typically, instead sat in a group gawping at telev
i
sion. Previous list of number of rooms very helpful, because often not shown a room for incapacitated residents, or an unheated annexe or miserable attic. Interviewed especially recent residents who would remember arriving. Longer stay residents are more 
likely to have a special relationship with the staff, and so get a better room, better chair, etc.
\par 
\par Contrast between extremes of a big old former workhouse for 500 or 1000 residents and a private residential home in a seaside town like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Worthing{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par First
 visit to Southern Grove in Stepney a shocking experience. As a young idealist believed the welfare state had abolished the workhouse, but here found old workhouse attitudes and inmates who were abject and disconsolate. Gaunt and vast, noise of trolleys o
n
 stone slabs. Dayrooms with up to 50 people watching an old black and white television set: often just sitting, rocking themselves. Little conversation. Women wore carpet slippers and aprons, men stained trousers, jackets and caps. Spectacles often tied t
ogether with string. Chipped mugs. Rushes to get meals, hoping for an extra biscuit. Very shocked by this dragooned mass warehousing.
\par 
\par Arrogant warden in his own spacious flat. When a visiting committee came, would get out the silver and serve a slap up lunch. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
Almost a class situation between staff and residents. Staff were especially able to control weak and infirm old people. Only subsequently realised the possibility that there was also extensive corruption: fiddling patients' pocket money or National A
ssistance. Staff tended to exaggerate the infirmities of residents. Discouraged them from going out into the nearby streets. Almost a quarter of all old people in homes were living in these big institutions. Many have been since pulled down, partly as a r
esult of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 .
\par 
\par Voluntary homes, such as those run by Methodists, were among the best. Not the Little Sisters of the Poor, which were more like workhouses, separating men from women, and favouring the men by giving them a glass of beer on Sundays
. But in general in voluntary homes the staff were most sensitive. Some were for occupational groups, such as doctors. This helps make friendships, which are in general rare in homes. Voluntary homes typically 30 or 40 residents.
\par 
\par Private homes varied in s
ize from 40 to 50 residents. Those which catered for the affluent often had subservient staff (who were caring partly because they had a chance of a legacy) and also good material facilities: radio and TV, heating, wardrobe, and space for valued possessio
n
s, photos etc. More common, however, were very small private homes where the residents lived in terror of the matron, and it was all run carefully for profit. Sometimes residents were scarcely fed, and had no contact with each other; it was like a small p
rison.
\par 
\par Wishes he had written up more notes immediately after visits and interviews. You need time, not only to interview, but to absorb what you hear and think about its structural meaning. You could dictate these impressions but then you have the problem 
of selection.
\par 
\par Novelty of a random survey of institutions. Showed that this was possible. Varied the number of residents they talked to according to the size of the home.
\par 
\par Attempted to introduce more order into comparisons and choice of examples by standar
dised ratings of physical amenities, occupational activities allowed, number of staff per resident, and levels of sociability of residents - whether they had friends in the home, how much they saw them, etc. Showed that degree of regimentation was related
 to staff levels. 
\par 
\par Realised that many residents did not need to be in homes: had recovered from an earlier episode of malnutrition, or from a stroke. Family too far away, or alienated. Developed a complex measure of disability to demonstrate this. Not just
 physical but also ability to talk, converse, go out. First step in arguing that they should be given e.g. nursing support at home, rather than live in an institution. Has since been developed into international classification of disability.
\par 
\par Very much inv
olved in the development of sheltered housing. Anxiety at the time at the rising cost of residential homes. Argued for the improvement of homes, but more people living at home. Raised other questions: home help service, substandard housing. He first used 
the term `sheltered housing'. Local, like older tradition of almshouses. Groups of 10 or 15. Opened one sheltered housing project himself in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Chatham{\*\xmlclose}
 in 1963: local authority, now voluntary. Sylvia Tunstall did some valuable research on sheltered housing but not enough of her work was published.
\par 
\par At present the elderly in homes are even more vulnerable because sources of finance are so insecure. Suspects that growth of privatisation has led to more profit-motivated and insufficiently regulated homes. Lip
 service was given to community care in the 1980s, but never the resources needed, so the gap is being filled by private market. Often most of the profits go to the manager.
\par 
\par Research team: preferred to have a very small number of interviewers working over a longer period. Two rooms in Skepper House in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bloomsbury{\*\xmlclose}. Four fifths of interviewing for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
 done by two people, and whole team only five. Included his wife Ruth, and Brian Rees, who also did statistical work. Bob Pinker the most import
ant help for the interviewing. Caroline Woodroffe a key organisational help. Sheila Benson, who became the project's manager, came to prepare study of old people in hospitals, but later also worked on poverty study. Skepper House then an active centre: Br
itish Sociological Association's office also there. At that time there was much more work involved e.g. in getting a questionnaire well printed.
\par 
\par Bob Pinker was very good-looking with an authoritative air. He had written a play about the workhouse and was then much more radical than later, when Peter differed with him on how to finance community care.
\par 
\par Peter wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  entirely himself, a
lthough to get comment he did try out a very few parts as papers first. Also wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Poverty in the UK}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
 singlehandedly, but co-authored one chapter with Dennis Marsden on lone parents, and one with Alan Walker on the elderly. General strategy of the latter research, and the original questionnaire, worked in close cahoots with Brain Abel-Smith.
\par 
\par Twice took jobs in institutions for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 . A week as an attendant at Cooper House, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Leicester{\*\xmlclose}. Also three or four days at a former workhouse for 500, Newholme, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}. Kept a diary. Remembers bathing an inmate.
\par 
\par At Newholme, c 1958-9, was an attendant looking after the bathing of old men. Struck by their institutionalised passivity, sense of neglect and abandonment; thinness; lack of personal cl
othing, institutionalised underwear; disciplinarian attitude of staff even to the physically infirm.
\par 
\par {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Katherine{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Buildings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, overlooked by the Mint, discovered by chance, c 1957. Built so that seven or eight single room flats had access along 
landings to water and toilet. Beatrice Potter was housing visitor there for Octavia Hill, followed by Ella Pyecroft. They both kept a diary. Peter found this. Decided to use the three months before he went from the Institute to LSE by revisiting the flats
 to record how the flats were now. Got a small grant to help the interviewing. Project was never published.
\par 
\par Found three women who had been there in Beatrice's day. The population was varied. Included many for whom these flats were the end of the road: ex-p
risoners, bachelor former seamen. But also first housing for young couples. So a mixture of the hopeful and the hopeless. Those on the way up included several brothers and sisters, who exchanged laundry and other help, and also looked after children for e
ach other, so could go out to work. Would love to write about it more, as a nodule of inner city experience.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Old People in Three Industrial Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
: perhaps the most important achievement was in establishing a method of international comparison. Book did
 not make a big impact. Confirmed some of the ideas he had developed in Bethnal Green. Based on a questionnaire study. This was also intended to have a national purpose as well as international. Resulted in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Aged in the Welfare State}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  with Dorothy Wedderburn, but they didn't really use the data: she wrote on income and employment, Peter on social security.

\par 
\par At the same time they collected interviews with old people in hospitals, including geriatric and mental hospitals. Other researchers were surprised th
at this was possible. This was analysed with Sheila Benson, and they wrote twelve chapters of a book on old people in hospitals. Peter was not satisfied with these drafts, and started to revise them, but half way through decided the task was too great, an
d that he should concentrate on the poverty research. Sheila Benson was very angry with him. Peter now feels very sorry about this. Has always tended to be over-optimistic about what he can achieve in a given time. 
\par 
\par The hospital book would have argued for redesigning hospitals as much more socially accommodating places, allowing patients to do more for themselves. Also, much miscategorisation of mental and chronic sick.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 24 January 1998
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Study of nursing homes with Caroline Woodroffe. She analysed the mater
ial and they wrote the book together. Why did people go into them rather than hospitals or homes for the elderly? Substudy based on 227 questionnaire replies, published as a short book for National Corporation of the Care of Old People. No study of them b
efore or since. Then only 20,000 beds, but now, due to government policy towards NHS, many more. 
\par 
\par Two big problems. Small authoritarian homes with vulnerable patients of 85 or 90 run by managers who were sometimes unqualified, or failed nurses pushed out b
y the NHS, or cynical moneymakers. Second problem was variation in material standards: some excellent, others poor food and little comfort, skimpy. Asked why were patients there, were they happy, could they receive visitors, etc. Nursing homes tended to c
luster in retirement towns where social services not well developed, and little supervision. 
\par 
\par For }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
, two important methodological innovations. One the measurement of disability, of incapacity for self-care, and also of capacity to communicate
. This instrument has been an important tool in social policy, and internationally. For example with meals on wheels, in deciding who needs meals most often. This measure led later to international classifications of disablement.
\par 
\par Second innovation was in 
sampling. Institutions vary enormously in size, from a few with several hundred to very many with a mere four to six beds. With normal sampling of the population in homes you would get large numbers of small homes but only a few of the largest. This means
 that a few large homes are assumed to be typical of most of them. Research projects spend too little time examining whether their cases are representative. Importance of being able to generalise from your cases.
\par 
\par Pride in this national study. Compares it w
ith Victorian Blue Books. But they were mainly based on secondhand evidence, while his small research team had collected the evidence systematically all over the country. Also pleased that he introduced a historical perspective to the analysis. The resear
ch was also rounded in that they interviewed not only elderly inmates but also the managers. Believes in multiple methods.
\par 
\par Need for the researcher to look at the whole course of human development
, and to ask whether people needed to have come to those homes. Perhaps if they had had a better diet when younger, they would not now suffer from Alzheimer's disease. Need to pre-empt disasters, so that people can stay longer in their own homes. In the s
ame way that early death can be reduced by preventative action, so can events of ageing like incarceration in an institution.
\par 
\par Would have liked to have looked more closely at individual people and their families. Paradox that they were often lonelier in an 
institution than alone at home. Staff are typically jocular with the elderly. They don't get to know each other. Residents come from different backgrounds, and have often got there because they are not good at intimate relationships. Need to understand ho
w they got there. And how sociability develops.
\par 
\par Capacity of the family to develop social networks better than voluntary or council agencies. Extended families can bring together three or four generations. Need to research these links. 
\par 
\par Starting with biogr
aphies of patients in homes. Rejects common staff view that they can't be interviewed. Staff need a means for engaging with the past of the people they are caring for. This should be part of the training of nurses and doctors. Could research work or a hou
sing estate also through biographies. How did tenants in high rise blocks get there? Need to establish some common patterns in analysing them. Understanding how people reach their situations will tell you much more about the structure of society.
\par 
\par Between finishing the fieldwork for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  in 1961 and embarking on the big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Poverty in the UK}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  project in 1967, two main paths. First was carrying out the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
Old People in Three Industrial Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  study, involving visits to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Copenhagen{\*\xmlclose} and contact with A
mericans. Also attempted but failed study of old people in hospitals. Second path was launching of programme of poverty studies, encouraged by first enthusiastic response in 1964 to proposal with Brian Abel-Smith to Joseph Rowntree Foundation. Launched a 
series of preparatory studies on key groups who had not been studied: Hilary Land on large families, published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Large Families in London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 ; Adrian Sinfield on the unemployed; John Veit Wilson on the sick and disabled; Dennis Marsden on lone parents, published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Mothers Alone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 . High quality of this new research team. All have gone on to success. But each also had difficulties. 
\par 
\par John Veit Wilson suffered from over anxiety in writing up. Always wanted to go on and do one more bit of research. There has to be a
 culmination. Peter failed himself on the hospitals project. John had this problem in his early research. Subsequently has been very productive, and made sharp contributions to the methodology of research into poverty.
\par 
\par John did lots of drafts but never reached a conclusion.
\par 
\par Adrian Sinfield had a purist attitude to research. His written work authoritative and reliable, wouldn't tolerate half-expressed ideas or unchecked references. But got diverted by teaching, and also by early 1970s project on sub-employ
ment: marginal employment and interrupted work careers. His big success in setting up the Unemployment Unit for research, still carrying on. Very much a team worker. Invaluable friend and colleague for Peter, keeping him in touch. Conscientious streak; ve
ry self-conscious, spare personality, not very confident. Successful partnership with his wife Dorothy, who has worked with him as an interviewer and Research Assistant. He finds it difficult to relax with others.
\par 
\par Dennis Marsden a rich personality. Integri
ty and honesty. Can be very self-revealing. A working class person made good: doesn't let you forget this. Strength of his roots. Went through a period of self-discovery as a writer. Earlier expression a little convoluted. Unfairly criticised by Titmuss. 
Diffidence towards other academics. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Mothers Alone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
 is still an inspiring book. When writing, would get up at four in the morning, and work with paper scattered all over his room. Then he would stick them together with sellotape, like Chinese rolls of script. Peter would stay with him when commuting to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}, during second divorce. Craftsman, perfectionist.
\par 
\par Hilary Land perhaps the most sustained close relationship. Was a mathematician, and originally came in to help them devise a sample. Peter then bec
ame interested in the way in which she wrote about the large families from the mothers' perspectives. She could not write well, unlike now, and Peter spent a lot of time rewriting her early drafts, which she accepted.
\par 
\par Peter has learnt to put these as suggestions, rather than like Michael Young, as corrections which he commanded the author to accept. The same approach with Ph D students.
\par 
\par When Peter moved to Bristol Hilary was there, so they renewed contact. Later she went on to be Professor at Queen Mary's, so they met less often in the 1980s-early 1990s. She is now back at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
. They worked together on pensions.
\par 
\par Michael Meacher was appointed as a gerontological research fellow, on money from the Sembal Trust, to do research on the mental handicapp
ed in homes for the elderly. Incredibly industrious, writing volumes from the start, very clever, but slow to find a clear sense of direction: couldn't organise his writing into a linear argument. But eventually, after he went to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}York{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, produced a draft that worked. His interest in politics developed as an intellectual challenge. He is not Machiavellian at all, a kind of innocent who still believes in the power of reason to change things. Incredibly industrious as an MP, masterin
g a whole succession of different briefs.
\par 
\par Shelia Benson managed all the interviewers, welding them into a team, a crucial role.
\par 
\par Alan Walker co-authored chapter on the elderly in the poverty study. He and his wife Carole were {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
 graduates. His early writing gauche and convoluted. Has since done important European research. A good colleague and friend.
\par 
\par Phil Holden was a very patient computer programmer. It's important to understand computing and numbers. Philip taught him novel w
ays of presenting information, selecting particular categories. It's important to develop your tables in stages. Don't jump in with all your questions or you will get so much printout that you can't wade through it. Explore step by step. Proceed in a dyna
m
ic relationship with the computer. First get the general outlines. Then try to break down the bigger groups into sub-groups. Third stage is being creative, putting groups together than you hadn't anticipated, or for example exploring gender in a new way. 

\par 
\par The fieldwork was finished by 1969. Delay in writing up partly due to Brian Abel-Smith pulling out in 1968. Also the technology was developing all the time. Many problems with it. It was then the largest memory package of any university. Other distraction
s being Chairman of Child Poverty Action, and setting up Disability Alliance. Believes in combining being a social scientist and a campaigner.
\par 
\par The book was really four volumes in one, 1200 pages. Wrote a supplementary short volume, never published, on gen
der and on inequalities in health. Introduction had been written two or three times already by end of 1960s; one version was published in a book by Dorothy Wedderburn. Periods of writing up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North Yorkshire
{\*\xmlclose}, and at Moreton-in-Marsh.
\par 
\par Growing realisa
tion that what was needed was not just a book on poverty in the 1960s, but an overview of the changing national structure two thirds of the way through the 20th century. Two often people dismiss work because it is a mere five years old. He shifted from wa
n
ting a quick report to aiming at a major contribution to thinking about poverty and the kind of institutional changes needed to reduce it. Wrote 28 chapters, four a year, finishing by 1978. Regrets that he did not use the more up-to-date index of deprivat
ion which is printed as an appendix, which had been evolved after the earlier analysis. 
\par 
\par Notable support of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Allen Lane{\*\xmlclose} and Penguin for the book. You need editorial support like a composer needs a good orchestra. Numerous spidery corrections to the man
uscript. It's worth spending time on such details. Is most proud of this of all his books.
\par 
\par Subsequent interest in cost of housing. Is it better to subsidise housing directly, or through housing benefits? Need also to look at subsidies to private housing t
hrough tax relief. Often those who took out mortgages in the long run had a very cheap option.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 20 February 1998
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Importance of trying to trace refusals. Researchers too often assume that their 10% or 20% of refusals are not significantly different from th
e remainder. Learnt to his cost through research on the elderly that the minority of refusals may be people who really matter for the general view: people who were so confused, or so severely disabled, or sick, that not possible to interview on the day of
 
the visit. So developed technique of using proxy interviews on their behalf, especially for mentally disabled. Important to always collect as much information as possible for a refuser or from those who refuse on their behalf, usually a relative. Started 
t
his in Bethnal Green, but systematised for the poverty study, in which used a mini-questionnaire for the interviewer to complete. Questions included the house and its ownership; how many lived there, and their age, and if possible, occupations. This mater
ial collected for the poverty study, but never analysed. Four-page leaflet. Some of the interviewers' managers objected that this was not a proper part of their work. 
\par 
\par Problems of representivity similarly for the Family Expenditure Study. At the top, a bit
 fluffy about the rich. Too few of them, and asked inappropriate set of questions. Similarly, among the poor the sick and disabled and extreme elderly are severely underestimated. It is intended to be a national survey of 10,000, but usually only 7,000 ho
u
seholds are interviewed. Comparison with the census shows includes too few over 75. Suspects the same would be true of young people who sleep at friends' homes, with no fixed address, but not homeless on the streets. Also ethnic minorities. New labour fle
xibility has meant more mobile population and family break-ups, so that it is not clear who really belongs to some households. General need for surveys to face the implications of more recent social changes.
\par 
\par Unemployment was featured in the poverty study, 
partly because there had been a sharp rise - albeit from a very low level - in 1967. Much bigger rises ten years later when Dennis Healey accepted spending cuts as part of IMF loan package after oil price rises. Subsequently grants from Rowntree and from 
S
ocial Science Research Council for modest follow-up on the unemployed. Carried out with Adrian Sinfield. Focussed also on `The Sub-employed', as report was titled, on those marginally or intermittently employed. But failed to bring the research to fruitio
n or to publish a book on this. The two research officers employed had been doing less than he thought.
\par 
\par A tightly controlled team works best when there has been a lot of preparation, and there is a clearly-defined problem to solve. More typically in scienc
e: social science is more discursive. He believed in giving people their heads, and sometimes that led to casualties. Social scientists face more difficult challenges than scientists, because they have to relate their findings to the overall social struct
ure in this country, and internationally. But unlike, say gravity, for scientists, social structure is not universal; it varies in very complex ways. Social science is more ambitious, just because, unlike physics, it cannot aim at finality.
\par 
\par The social scie
ntist faces questions about advancing knowledge which are not so much linear as multidimensional. So a research team should be collaborative, rather than directed. Important to allow some of the less inexperienced new members to develop ideas of their own
 
and carry out their research. Against determination by a figure on high. Creativity needed not only in conceiving a project but also in the fieldwork stage. You should draw on the diversity within the team. Allow flexibility of input. His own creative inp
ut also to pull it together at the end. Learning on his feet all the time. Did not pretend to have all the answers.
\par 
\par Dislike of the Austrian and German tradition of a professorship as a fiefdom, with other lecturers whose jobs depended entirely on the few professors, who told them what to research and then put their name to what was published. Visited 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Austria{\*\xmlclose}. Abhorred that. Met a professor who showed him round, who was the ruler of the roost in ways which surprised him. 
\par 
\par Research councils and foundati
ons also prefer to give grants to known academics, who they can trust to produce a final report. Because it is more difficult for unknown juniors to get research awards in their own name, established academics may sign for one of their projects without kn
o
wing much about the work. This can go badly wrong. To some extent with the sub-employed project. But more so with a project on educational opportunity and the connection between A levels and social class in terms of family background. Researcher took the 
view that the results were not worth writing up. Peter could see more in the print-outs; and he was held responsible by the Department of Education. So he had to write the report himself. 
\par 
\par He discovered that going to university was not only related to social class of parents, but also grandparents. In other words, that whole family background counted more than father's occupation. In the poverty study they had already begun to take into acc
ount mother's as well as father's occupations in the household, which was innovative.
\par 
\par Inequalities in health: began with giving the Sir Geoffrey Vickers Lecture, which was published in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Lancet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
 in 1974. Raised issues about the relationship between class 
structure and mortality, and policy ways of addressing these structural issues. Ideas about giving children a better start are a tradition in health, but not clearly enough related to class structure. 19th century work on malnutrition and slum housing. Ha
d intended second volume of poverty book with four chapters on health, which he drafted. 
\par It would be interesting to take a group interviewed, and trace through the Registrar of Deaths when they actually died. At this time, Peter was also writing on old people in hospitals.
\par 
\par Suspects it was through the advice of Brian Abel-Smith that David Ennals as Minister for Health invited him to become a member of a research group on Inequalities in Health under Sir Douglas Black. It came out of the blue, and Peter jump
ed at it. Not a large widely representative commission, but just a small research group of four.
\par 
\par However, whenever they met there were 15 or 20 from the Department of Health, such as the Chief Medical Officer, the Permanent Secretary, etc. Civil servants 
and advisers. Began to realise that this larger group were assuming they could steer the outcome. But also saw that only the four appointees had to sign the report: Sir Douglas Black, who had become President of the Royal College of Physicians; Gerry Morr
is, Professor of Epidemiology at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine; and Cyril Smith, of the Social Science Research Council. When Peter saw the draft report he didn't like it at all: too thin. Got Gerry Morris's support, and able to ta
ke the re-write into the hands of the four appointees. Stuart Bloom, as secretary to the committee, proved very helpful. Wrote a 400-page report.
\par 
\par However, caught by the early election. The new Thatcher government dismissed it entirely. They did not even c
onsider the cost-free recommendations. The Department smuggled out the report on an August Bank Holiday weekend, printing only 250 copies. Outraged BMA, trade unions, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Lancet}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 , whole medical profession, that topic treated with such derision. Then reproduced 
in large quantities, and finally reprinted as a Penguin book. Still used as a text. Has added new research findings in subsequent editions. Subsequently also Margaret Whitehead has updated the original report as `The Health Divide', and both are published
 together in the latest Penguin edition.
\par 
\par The earlier draft report had simply lacked depth. No suggestions of relevant action possible in housing or by Treasury. No new research for the final report: too quick. Gerry Morris especially helped. Some shrewd co
mments by Black. The most difficult problem was their attempt to measure how far illnesses were due to biological or social factors like smoking and drinking. Nobody had done this properly then. And also, they did not pull together the international compa
r
isons well enough. The strengths of the report were especially to show that health inequalities were widening, even though absolute health was improving. Clearly genetic factors important, and also individual behaviour, such as eating too much fat or smok
i
ng. But their most original conclusion was that material deprivation accounted for more than half of the differences in health between the rich and the poor, rather than genes or behaviour. Including differences in housing and environmental pollution, and
 deprivation at work, such as exposure, such as exposure to horrendous dust or noise or abrasive thumps on their bodies. 
\par 
\par More research is needed to identify which forms of deprivation mattered most. There is a lot of research on the relationship between d
amp housing and asthmatic and respiratory disease. But not at work, where the focus has been on safety and machinery, rather than on respiratory disease. We don't know how the effects of work pollution and home pollution balance. 
\par 
\par In the report it was suggested that the connection between income inequalities and health lasted into old age.
\par 
\par This was more debatable, partly because class measurement of the old is more difficult. The Census Longitudinal Study of 1981-91, however, has sharpened this conclusion.
\par 
\par Gerry Morris was a mercurial and innovative man, one of the key figures in British social medicine. Got to know him at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Wrote important textbook on epidemiology. His study of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose} bus drivers and conductors show
ed that the drivers suffered from more heart disease than the conductors, for now obvious reasons. He invited Peter to lecture at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 in the sixties after meeting him in a small debating group on health and society at the London School of Hygie
ne. His ideas spilled out, to the extent that he couldn't always get them into order. He found difficulty in finishing reports and selecting what was most important. But a lot of his instincts were correct. He was an innovator without being a systematiser
.
\par 
\par Stuart Bloom was useful and important, a civil servant who knew how to behave, subservient and careful, meticulous and authoritative. But he was also richer in person than in his bureaucratic role. He wrote well. He was genuinely interested in the theory
 of science, and indeed has since become a professor of science in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Amsterdam{\*\xmlclose}
, writing erudite scientific papers. He had a handicapped son and so had looked into the inadequacies of therapy and service in relation to handicap. He wrote minutes and draft reports and fashioned the agendas for meetings.
\par 
\par Nicky Hart at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} was appointed as research secretary to the group. She explored the material in depth, and brought ideas to the group, including a debate on causation. Stuart Bloom had written the 
first draft and she redid it, especially in relation to children's health. Much argument followed. Her abilities are in raising sharp and unusual questions, and taking an unorthodox view, but she was often unable to systematise her thinking or specify the
 precise documentary evidence. It was a very constructive combination. Some of the best scientific results come from conflict and argument, and the process was somewhat harrowing. Unfortunately Nicky later felt that she had not been fully appreciated.

\par 
\par After the Black report, Peter has continued to develop the analysis of health deprivation. This started with research in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
, where he had moved in 1982. Did an analysis of health differences between the city's wards, published in 1984, which made qui
te a splash. Also published in an international journal. Worked with people in planning and in health departments. Social indicators included employment, housing condition and tenure, whether electricity cut off, and free school meals. Compared this with 
mortality and found very close correlations. Peter did some visits to wards and informal interviews for this research.
\par 
\par Then invited by the Northern Regional Health Authority to prepare a report on deprivation and health in the north-east. Because he was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}
, has had lots of contacts with the region. Looked at 686 wards, with Alasdair Beatty, a statistician working for the health authority, and Peter Phillimore, now at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose}, but then employed by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}. 
Report again showed strong correlations. Rural areas were more problematic, because much very localised variety with small pockets, contrasting poor villages with well off commuters. This attracted much attention, particularly for the index of deprivation
, which is still used. David Gordon at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} has improved it subsequently. Peter spoke widely about the report. 
\par 
\par Has kept a close and affectionate relationship with Peter Phillimore, a man of judgement. He went on to compare Middlesbrough with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Sunderland{\*\xmlclose}
, equally industrial, but with a lower death rate. He suggested that this was due to the higher level of environmental pollution in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Peter has produced a similar report on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}, 90-page short monograph, intended to help with planning. Has also been involved with similar work in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cumbria
{\*\xmlclose} and Merseyside.
\par 
\par Invited by Greater London Council in mid-1980s to carry out a new survey of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose} life and labour, interviewing 2500 people, and focussing on income, employ
ment and health. Intended this to be in an integrated way, but disappointed, because it was only written up and published piecemeal in different books and papers. Could well be repeated.
\par 
\par Most recently, with David Gordon in 1997-8 was commissioned to write a second report on health and inequalities in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
, tracing changes since the 1980s. Complicated by changes in the ward areas. Has just completed the report for the Leverhulme Trust. Shows how some of the earlier worst wards have changed somewhat,
 such as Ashley ward, with a black minority, where the 1981 riots took place, where investment has improved housing and employment. By contrast working-class wards with high-rise housing like Lawrence Hill have dropped to the bottom because of high unempl
oyment.
\par 
\par David Gordon is now mapping the country, identifying wards with high deprivation and health problems. Thus councils will have no excuse in avoiding selective prioritisation. There are 10,500 wards in the country, and Lawrence Hill is 230th from wor
st. It is in Bristol East, the city centre, an area of 1960s high-rise housing which has deteriorated. The council has not enough money for repair and modernisation. Now has a concentration of unemployed, lone parents and homeless. This undermines possibi
l
ity of self-help in the community: at a certain point, if there are too many in need, community help becomes hopeless. Gordon's mapping exposes the polarisation going on in the country. Lawrence Hill is in the worst 5% in the country, but the city also in
cludes wards like Westbury-on-Trim, in the top 10%.
\par 
\par The research is also valuable because it exposes how it is the structure which needs changing, not just more money in particular places. Once the deprived wards are identified, qualitative studies are als
o essential. We need to understand the relationship between changing social structure and individual experience.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 22 May 1998
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The international side of Peter's research grew like Topsy. He probably first became aware of the international dimension through the influence of Peter Marris in discussions about 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kenya{\*\xmlclose}. He discovered that there had been followers of Booth and Rowntree scattered through the Empire, for example in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}India{\*\xmlclose} and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South Africa{\*\xmlclose}. These largely followed British lines, although in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South Africa{\*\xmlclose}
 they innovated with a `Poverty Datum Line'. Decided that the major research on poverty must be based in international perspective, and therefore held an international conference, whose papers were published in 1970. Has himself only ca
rried out two tentative pieces of research overseas.
\par 
\par In 1980 given support by UNESCO for a pilot study of poverty and social policy in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kenya{\*\xmlclose}. Visited {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kenya{\*\xmlclose}
 for some weeks and interviewed politicians and civil servants. Decided to build on some good surveys which had been carried out in 1970s, and interview in three areas, using African interpreters. Visited two areas, and carried out some interviews in a 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nairobi{\*\xmlclose} shantytown, in one tiny area called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kitui{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Village{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} visiting nearly
 every household, living in makeshift tents of black plastic bags. Impressed by the resilience of some in nevertheless organising family life, with tablecloths and well-arranged pots and pans and great hospitality. Learned a lot about the dignity and soci
ability of African families. Still has the photographs which he took then. Intended a study of poverty and national development.
\par 
\par The Indian story is even briefer, arising from a visit in the mid-1980s with his wife Jean, when they saw a makeshift school in a poor part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}New Delhi{\*\xmlclose}
, for children who otherwise would have no education at all. They are themselves financing two children through school there. 
\par 
\par Neither initiative came to anything. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kenya{\*\xmlclose}, when Peter discovered he was being paid on a w
hite colonialist's rate, he asked for his three African colleagues to be paid the same, or for the money to be divided equally between the four of them. UNESCO refused and Peter resigned. He has regretted this failed project ever since, and that he did no
t press it with other agencies. For {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}India{\*\xmlclose}, he was encouraged to apply for a research fellowship to study poverty in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}India{\*\xmlclose}
, but after a change of government this was withdrawn.
\par 
\par The support he gives in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}India{\*\xmlclose} is through Deepalaya, which aims to
 establish a lifelong commitment from people who have money to others in the world, to invest in the education, right through school, of children from the poorest areas of the city. A very crowded area, teeming with life, people gathering around water poi
n
ts, narrow winding alleys, often with sewage in gutters. Minute stores with people selling tiny quantities of foodstuffs and tins. The school he visited was very crowded, children sitting cross-legged on dusty floor, not enough paper or crayons, but extra
o
rdinarily inventive and polite and disciplined, an oasis of calm. Willingness to learn, not only of children but also mothers. Also struck by the commitment of the people who had founded the school. He also felt their own contribution however small would 
be lasting. An example of how despite desperate circumstances, and lack of structural help from governments, and predatory international market, something can be done: a glimmer of hope in a sea of pessimism. 
\par 
\par In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nairobi{\*\xmlclose} slum villages, interested by t
he role of the elders, shadow tribal organisation, despite high mobility. Found spokespersons for the area. On one occasion young men gathered around him threateningly but older women saw him safely off the site.
\par 
\par Visits brought home that we have a lot to 
learn from poorer societies, especially about what we have lost through the process of industrialisation. Techniques for managing safe water; medicinal properties of plants. International agencies measure through material progress, such as number of telev
i
sion sets. But what about the number of suicides or criminal rapes? Because of narrative ability, very important things are handed down between generations. And now they are surfing the Internet without being able to read. The extended family has been les
s interfered with by bureaucrats in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}India{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par This led to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 International Analysis of Poverty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
. Need to get international backing for an `international poverty line'. At United Nations World Summit in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Copenhagen{\*\xmlclose}
 in 1995 it was agreed by 117 countries that poverty was a problem affecting all countries, whether rich or poor, and studies should be carried out. So far actually few: {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Denmark{\*\xmlclose}, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Netherlands{\*\xmlclose}. Needs following up.
\par 
\par UNDP recognition that absolute poverty occurs also in rich countries is the thin end of a useful intellectual wedge. Certainly true of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
: homeless. Some of situations in densely packed cities may be as serious as rural poverty in poor countries. Has visited waste ground in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}New York{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Chicago
{\*\xmlclose}, littered with empty bottles and drug needles, far worse than rural poverty in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bangladesh{\*\xmlclose}. 
\par 
\par It is also useful to expand international concepts of poverty beyond the material, to communication and health an
d education, and also ability to fulfil social obligations as workers or family members. It is possible that differences between rich and poor within countries will become more significant than between them. Explosion of studies of globalisation. It is of
ten more rewarding to study trends than differences, because trends point to influences. For example, the fantastic growth of inequality in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose} in last twenty years.
\par 
\par Peter's earlier work on poverty showed especially how it was due not only to unem
ployment, ill-health etc, but also to earlier lack of education. From 1970s became aware of globalising influences. Coca Cola sold and television watched everywhere. We no longer depend on seasons of produce like strawberries. Massive mergers. Now 37 inte
rnational companies each has a turnover larger than state of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}
. Immensely important organisations, but socially and ethically not accountable. On the contrary, they are forcing us to demolish the defences against unregulated capitalism built up b
y the welfare state since the 1890s. Also growth of international agencies. All this was the subject of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 The International Analysis of Poverty}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 , written in 1993.
\par 
\par In the 1990s has worked as a consultant to UNDP and also to European Commission. Appointed by UNDP to visit {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Georgia{\*\xmlclose}
 after the civil war. Visited in 1994 for a few weeks, to advise on the democratic evolution of the state, including welfare and safety nets for the impoverishment resulting from the abandonment of Communism. Interested in transiti
onal economies. Learnt that there had been inflation of 2000%. The result was that old welfare policies were now a sham. In many ways an admirable society. More doctors per thousand than anywhere else in the world, including 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}USA{\*\xmlclose}. High proportions also
 of nuclear physicists, musicians and artists. Very beautiful mountains and old buildings. Highly developed history. Also it had one of the best social security systems in the world: a more elaborate and generous pensions scheme than 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Sweden{\*\xmlclose}. But people who treasured these things and could have helped to build a democratic society were being sidelined, in favour of those subservient to crude westernisation and marketisation.
\par 
\par Discovered there were two sorts of mafia in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Georgia{\*\xmlclose}. One were former Sovi
et bosses, especially of Defence Ministry and the army, who were lining their pockets by using military trucks to sell petrol at exorbitant prices. The other were get-rich-quick from western markets supplying cigarettes, Coca Cola or other goods in short 
supply from kiosks, rather like car boot sales. Saw them two or three times in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tbilisi{\*\xmlclose}, young men with machine guns in BMWs. Few other cars on the streets.
\par 
\par Story of woman who had to take a hen around from street to street to find sufficient for it to peck and feed. Pensioners starving, because a pension formerly worth \'a3
50 a week was now worth only 50p. Unemployment pay not worth the bus fare to collect it. People dying in hospitals, where the nurses couldn't get food or salaries. Some nurses gave up, but others struggled on.
\par 
\par International neglect of the issues in rapid economic transition of the need to provide safety nets by adjusting benefits, and to tax new money. He found that IMF and World Bank delegations had no interest at all in this.
\par 
\par People he has worked with on poverty include Tony Atkinson, now Warden of Nuffield College; Alan Walker at Sheffield; and especially David Gordon at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}. Worked with Gordon on the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose} survey, and he bettered Peter's index with his `linear discrimi
natory analysis', showing there was a threshold of poverty beyond which the experiences of deprivation were multiplied disproportionately by lowering income. Threshold is a widely used concept in environmental and health questions. David Gordon brought it
 in through his background as a geologist and statistician. They have been a good collaborative partnership, and are now working together with others at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
 on the new third Breadline Britain Survey, jointly with Loughborough and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}York{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Universities{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. They are also collaborating in trying to get the Copenhagen Declaration activated.
\par 
\par David Gordon is sharp witted, can sum up effectively. Likes his humour. Mutual respect. Can see through pretence easily, prick a balloon. Willing to be political.
\par 
\par Bledwyn Davies, who has been running the Personal Social Service Research Unit for many years ... recently told him that he'd agreed with the Department of Health that he would only get research money so long as he stayed out of politics. Wonders w
hether the intention of the Department is to produce unreadable reports which nobody reads. All research has political implications. You are either accepting and therefore reinforcing the status quo or you are questioning it. Everything you write has a po
litical implication: you can't avoid it.
\par 
\par Tony Atkinson is someone he appreciates for pursuing similar paths. Is a better economist and a better mathematician. Dry quality: he succeeds through understatement. His work cumulates.
\par 
\par Opponents include rash poli
ticians like John Moore, Secretary of State for Social Security in 1989, who claimed that poverty did not exist in 1989. Tendency especially of governments to believe that poverty does not exist in their own country, but in others, and that they cannot do
 anything about other countries. Wish to keep down public expenditure is an international phenomenon. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose} should do more for overseas aid.
\par 
\par Current UNDP annual report shows many connections, for instance between poverty and human rights, or poverty
 and civil war. But World Bank looks at poverty myopically in terms simply of the international market. Internationally, the poorest countries have got poorer since 1960s. Many radical reports from international agencies, but little action. Few people wri
ting effectively about international social policy. Exceptions include Chomsky and John Pilger.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \ul\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 14 September 1998
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Move to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} unexpected. Received a letter in 1962 from Alber
t Sloman. Very precise, compact, former RAF pilot. Never liked a stray letter on his desk when he interviewed you. This immaculate tidiness also a weakness. Kept the university grounds like a billiard table. Perhaps a sign of insecurity. But efficient at 
getting things done. Noel Annan, as chair of Academic Advisory Committee, had suggested Peter for professor of sociology.
\par 
\par Deliberate idea to start with a few large departments, which could soon compete with those in other universities. Problem that they th
en also had to include sub-disciplines which elsewhere were separate departments: for example social anthropology or social psychology or social policy and administration in relation to sociology.
\par 
\par Titmuss tried to dissuade him from going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}. Un
comfortable meeting of over two hours in his Ealing home when they debated. Peter felt it was a huge opportunity and he simply had to take it. Felt as if it had been bequeathed to him. So met Sloman and Annan and all was confirmed.
\par 
\par It is hard to know, but probably the basic ideas for the university came from Noel Annan. Sloman lacked imagination, but he could give them precision. They were also expanded by Jean Floud and Kenneth Capon. 
\par 
\par Peter liked the idea of big departments partly because his experience
 of competing departments at LSE. Sociology at LSE was both eclectic and uncreative and he hoped that a new department could do all the things it wasn't doing. Titmuss was flabbergasted by Peter going.
\par 
\par Noel Annan was a very cultured and creative man with lots of good ideas, not all of which he could sustain, and a congenial personality. Persuaded Peter because he believed {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
 needed social arithmetic. But Peter was more ambitious. Sociology of rising esteem in the 1960s. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Opportunity{\*\xmlclose} to realise this.
\par 
\par Noel Annan had the seminal ideas for the university. Showed Peter the draft of the Reith lectures. Kenneth Capon had the idea of building in the valley with high rise towers and a spine road, leaving the flatter landscape intact: a blow against ur
ban sprawl. 
\par 
\par Sociology was then little developed in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
. He was the seventh or eighth professor. The only strong department was that at LSE, which was much criticised. Peter wanted to bring sociology together with social policy and administration. And also to incorporate other developments as in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}America{\*\xmlclose}. Remembers discussions at tea with Jean Blondel, professor of politics, and Dick Lipsey, of economics. Lipsey at this time seemed sympathetic to Keynesianism and agreed to teaching about unemp
loyment, which he never carried out. His department became narrowly based on mathematical economics, econometrics, close to monetarism. Lipsey recruited too many specialists unsuited to general teaching, and the turnover in his department proved very fast
.
 Peter was pressed by Lipsey to appoint people in his own mould, and so had to think out what he wanted. Decided to aim for a catholic department, taking the best of a cluster of approaches. Early appointments included social policy, social history, mathe
m
atical sociology and social anthropology. Takes pride in achievements of mathematical sociology and social history as well as social policy. Able to make good and lasting appointments. David Lockwood came from LSE and not so broadminded, but went along wi
th Peter's approach, and has provided important stability.
\par 
\par Wanted the department not only to be adventurous and pioneering, but also democratic. Also led in widening social basis of student intake. In one of his last classes, three black students, a former
 Ford shop steward, two nurses in mid years, and two or three from Asia. Went for mature students very early. Decided to teach an MA, including mature students, in the first teaching year of the university, 1964-5. This broadening of the intake was an imp
ortant innovation.
\par 
\par So was the tripartite system of assessment which they devised, including coursework essays, take-home exams, and traditional exams. However, staff found this meant too much marking, and some other departments were hostile, so it was severely modified.

\par 
\par Projects also built into the system. Peter secured posts of two project officers, parallel to laboratory officers in science, an idea which Sloman later dropped. Developing students' research skills, graduate and undergraduate, and helping 
them to realise their ideas in projects.
\par 
\par There was originally no separation of staff and student social facilities at the university. For many years Peter successfully opposed the setting up of a Senior Common Room. Scientists not happy at this. It helped
 the democratic atmosphere at the university, expressed also in the big assemblies in 1968 which were attended not only by staff and students but also by secretaries, porters and cleaners. Doubts whether Sloman had the idea of mixed facilities. He was lef
t-wing, but social democrat rather than socialist. Does not know where the idea came from of treating students as adults and not supervising their accommodation.
\par 
\par Kenneth Capon: a very interesting man, urbane, house in Hampstead Garden Suburb. But old fashi
oned ideas about households and how to manage students. The student towers would have worked better if they had had the space he originally envisaged. Peter later opposed building more. Regrets he did not involve himself earlier in the design.
\par 
\par Peter and A
lan Gibson, professor of physics, were the first two academic staff appointed, and recruited all the first students for October 1964. As a result, involved in everything, including appointing committees for science. At that stage, no structure of accounta
b
ility. So it was easier for people with ideas to get their way. Capon was planning for a university of 10,000. But how would a university on stilts function if half-built? You have to be able to build piecemeal, with each part functioning well separately.

\par 
\par Jean Blondel a very Gallic teacher, could be humorous, but also very vague, a non-professional philosopher. Attractive manner, and won many arguments for politics, building it up with a good image. But rather conservative too.
\par 
\par Peter wanted a survey centre for the university but the data archive idea won through, very much at Blondel's insistence. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} does now have a panel survey, but this should have come much sooner. 

\par 
\par 1968 crisis. There was a revolutionary potential in 
the ideas on which the university was based. Students influenced by events on the continent. Started with the interruption of a lecturer from Porton Down, and vice chancellor excluding three students. Issue of free speech versus stopping chemical warfare.
 Escalated, until eventually assemblies of the entire university, over a thousand, students and staff. 
\par 
\par Sloman later, in 1973-4, with continuing student protest, came close to being pushed out; Noel Annan was brought in and wrote a report which poured oil 
on troubled waters. Sociologists united in backing the students and more democracy. Students found a way of blocking the spine road with small pickets and preventing key deliveries. Removed by police, and then reinforced, until the police had arrested ove
r
 a hundred. Peter intervened and went with the Deputy Chief Constable to ask the vice chancellor to agree to a stand-off, but he seemed stunned and unable to offer a rational view. But police nevertheless did stand off. On an earlier occasion students had
 locked in the senate, and police refused to come to help.
\par 
\par It was almost impossible in these years to reconcile the libertarian democratic principles being developed at the university with an elitist view of university rule. 1968 was exhilarating, but when
 nothing happened a mood of frustration and anarchy set in, with graffiti and some arson, and even a few students becoming pro-terrorism. Also free love and drug culture. 
\par 
\par Peter tried to play a mediating role, and was eventually chosen by senate as a Pro-
Vice-Chancellor against Sloman's recommendation, a unique vote. Sloman then treated him in a very condescending way, even covertly suggesting that he did no teaching and research in the university, and was always outside dealing with Child Poverty Action 
Group etc. He was told this by Ian Proudman, professor of mathematics. In fact these other activities were in his spare time. The sociology department even had weekly administrative meetings on Monday mornings.
\par 
\par Earlier he had been quite close to Albert. First doubts when he basked in the glory of having his special house built on campus, using too many resources: Peter thought he should have bought a house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester
{\*\xmlclose} with a mortgage. But his personality not a crucial factor in 1968 events.
\par 
\par They would have happened anyway. Cultural change of the period. Many of the more radical young people were choosing to come to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}: nonconformists, also women students.
\par 
\par Pro-Vice-Chancellor for three years. Proud of holding rents down. Also of establishing the day nursery. And special provisions for the disabled. Tried but failed to get a policy for disabled students at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol
{\*\xmlclose}. Had to fight long and hard for each. Learnt a lot about university politics and administration. Moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} in January 1982.
\par 
\par Didn't want to leave {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}. Left because he fell in love with Jean, a quite different kind of relationship. Over five hours commuting from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}
 was too much for him. Also especially busy because giving talks in many places on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Poverty in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}UK{\*\xmlclose}.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419  Then by accident in 1980, travelling with David Donnison, discovered that {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
 were seeking a replacement for Roy Parker, who had been unwell. David put Peter's name forward and the VC Alec Merrison invited Peter to interview in early 1981. Peter appointed, although continued teaching at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose} until the end of the year.
\par 
\par While the experience of Essex was of novelty and expansion, at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} it was of decline and conformity. Attempts to stop the destruction of the departmen
ts of drama and architecture. Found himself moving from a very large to a very small department of social policy, too hooked up with social work. All the social science departments at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
 small. Much of this self-induced. Thus Michael Banton had secured an ESRC Race Relations Centre, and then allowed its transfer to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Warwick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid598493 {\*\xmlclose}. Banton }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 a right-wing yes-man. Social science split up between individual specialists with little cohesion, and this proved very difficult to change.
\par 
\par Peter did secure one academic appointment in the 1980s, Sarah Payne, who had been his PhD student, and another when the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Exeter{\*\xmlclose}
 department of social policy was closed. Wanted 15 permanent staff but never convinced the VC. Alec Merrison was disinterested in the social scienc
es, and his successor Sir John Kingman even more so: an urbane conservative, but a disaster for the university. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} is based on departments rather than broader faculties or schools of study.
\par 
\par Thrown in at the deep end. But fulfilled one ambition: each year he was able to teach one course at every level - first year, second year, third year, and graduate. Also pleased to introduce more mature students. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Bristol{\*\xmlclose} had a reputation of being a finishing school for girls who hadn't made it to Oxbridge. Upset that he couldn't make headway on access for disabled students.
\par 
\par Developed health studies at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}. Had tried, but not succeeded, to develop a degree in nursing there in 1960s. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
 has important health research, but balkanised: George Davey-Smith in epidemiology, Daniel Dorling in social geography. And David Gordon.
\par 
\par But on the whole {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} has been an uphill and disappointing struggle.
\par 
\par Political campaigns: has been aware from his first research that his work
 has political implications, and the connections between research and action. Since he became a socialist at school. Was a Fabian at 17. Sensitivity to political expression much developed through working with Michael Young. Seeing the dark side of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Berlin{\*\xmlclose} and of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}
. In 1950s became immersed in the back room of the Labour Party, working with Titmuss and Abel-Smith on pensions. Found himself speaking at party meetings and ward branches, and trade union meetings and conferences. From 1954 until
 1980s served on Labour Party back bench committees on welfare and pensions.
\par 
\par Douglas Jay caustic, full of self-importance, orthodox Treasury view, unimaginative and uncreative on social security. So were the trade unions, but they had interests to protect.
\par 
\par Dick Crossman a friend and colleague over many years. Became an adversary in the late 1960s when CPAG was arguing for more redistribution. One of the three best minds he has ever met. Earlier, overwhelmed by his intellectual versatility and tenacity and
 dexterity, made Peter feel second-rate by comparison. But not consistent. He would seize an idea, pursue it, and then relinquish it.
\par 
\par Socratic ability to knock the bottom out of your argument, even if you were a friend. Sparkling vivacity. Could speak eff
ectively, loquaciously, without notes. His civil servants found him very uncomfortable, restless mind always questioning, racing on beyond the brief he had given them. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Wilson{\*\xmlclose}
 made a mistake in not appointing him Secretary of State for Health and Social Security sooner. 
\par 
\par Plans had been worked out, and if they had been implemented in 1964-6, they could have changed the whole shape of English class, and made {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}England{\*\xmlclose} closer to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Sweden
{\*\xmlclose}. Pensions, low pay, sickness and unemployment pay all needed r
eforms. Takes politics seriously, although can also be fun. Possibility of bringing about structural changes which will affect millions. Bruising conflict with Labour in 1969-70 when argued that poverty was being made worse. Hostility of Crossman, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Peter{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Shore{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Wilson{\*\xmlclose}
. Acrimony again when Heath and his successors tried to blame poverty on parents and family influences. Some beneficial small advances under Labour 1974-9, especially disability benefits, through Alf Morris, with Abel-Smith in the
 background. From the late 1970s Peter no longer an important political influence, through the lean Thatcher years and after. All through, was on Labour Backbench Committees on social policy. These depended very much on the chairman. Barbara Castle tried 
to rush through business so that she could get away quickly.
\par 
\par Lack of hard-headed planning behind New Labour. Chaotic, whether in terms of Frank Field or Harriet Harman or Gordon Brown or Blair. 
\par 
\par Worked for several years with Frank Field. Tony Lynes had effectively been director of CPAG, but likes to work singlehandedly, and not with a team, and decided to retire. Frank Field, a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 borough councillor, then relatively unknown, appointed to succeed him. First two years, learning on the job: at the st
art he was ill organised in thinking and wrote unattractively, but improved. Frank was off ill during the crisis months in 1969-70 when in conflict with the Labour government and David Ennals as minister. From the Heath government, Frank developed as a ve
r
satile political campaigner. Self-made and self-important man. Backed by CPAG teamwork, which sparked him into doing creative and influential things, but also gave him a disciplined framework. He failed to see the importance of this framework. Began to be
 restive, and published his own pamphlet supporting the sale of council houses. Wanted to be his own boss. To his credit, set up the Low Pay Unit. 
\par 
\par Resigned when elected an MP. Peter not artful as politician, but he suspects that Frank was trying to create
 a situation in which he could resign from CPAG claiming it was in the hands of Militant. As chairman Peter avoided this. Has become very critical of Frank's contribution to social policy. His current views, pandering to the right by exaggerating fraud an
d pretending without any evidence that the private sector could provide universal welfare, is hypocritical and destructive. A considerable person, but a loner, who has raised a lot of expectations which he cannot deliver. 
\par 
\par A painful story. Likes to be able
 to work with people with mutual respect, as with David Gordon, or his present work on poverty with Sarah Payne and Ruth Levitas, and on health with Margaret Whitehead. Hoped for that with Frank Field in 1967-73, but ended in disappointment. As others hav
e found.
\par 
\par CPAG founded with Tony Lynes in mid-1960s, a time when there was a wider growing recognition that governments had not solved the problems of poverty: Shelter, Oxfam, also express this view. CPAG founded through an alliance between concerned social
 workers, especially Quakers, and academics.
\par 
\par Fred Philp was chair of the Family Welfare Association of the Society of Friends. Brian Abel-Smith gave the first address which galvanised people. Launched with big publicity in December 1965 and received courteously in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Downing Street{\*\xmlclose}
 by Harold Wilson. Tony Lynes was the first secretary, preparing press releases and delivering them by bicycle. But the group grew, with branches, and a legal side started by Audrey Harvey and Rosalind Brooke. Tony resigned bec
ause he did not like being a manager. They got initial support from Alan Sainsbury. CPAG's main source of income has been sale of its welfare rights handbooks. But has also had grants from Astor Foundation and Rowntree. Membership small but active, with a
round 25 branches. Some have local pamphlets and local advice centres. They used to have stalls in market streets. He used to sell pamphlets himself in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose} with Adrian Sinfield.
\par 
\par Tony Lynes was secretary for four years, then Frank Field was dire
ctor for ten years. He was succeeded by Ruth Lister, then Sally Witcher, and now Martin Barnes. Peter retired as chairman after 20 years in 1989, and became president. He still goes to some meetings and sometimes speaks for CPAG. However, stayed on as cha
irman of Disability Alliance as it was going through a rocky patch. Chairman's role involves five executive and twelve sub-committee meetings a year; staff pay meetings; money-raising; annual reports and the annual meetings; and visits to branches.
\par 
\par Ruth Lister was a student at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} c 1970, and came to CPAG as a research officer to write a series of pamphlets. She was a better director than Frank.
\par 
\par Disability {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Alliance{\*\xmlclose} was founded in 1973 with Alan Walker. A young Essex graduate, he had written about the elderly with Peter, and also a chapter in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 Poverty in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}UK{\*\xmlclose}.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6648419\charrsid6648419 
 Illustrates arbitrariness of compensation through the courts for disability due to accidents: illustrates with case of student disabled in motorbike accident. Called for a compensatio
n scheme based on National Insurance: government reply derisory. Decided to set up a campaigning body. Peter had time, since he was rather lonely in the evenings, going through divorce. With Alan devised and wrote a Disability Rights handbook, edited by B
renda Corti, to provide a basic income for the group. Over six million disabled in the population. Did secure some real improvements through Alf Morris in 1974-9.
\par 
\par This was really the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}high point{\*\xmlclose} of the work of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Alliance{\*\xmlclose}
. Subsequent ups and downs, including problems with staff politics and with equal pay when they were putting in very unequal effort. This can create destructive jealousies. CPAG also had equal pay. Some left-wingers more concerned with their own salvation
 than the cause itself. Chairman's role, as at CPAG, was to mediate. Typically, little problem in the idealistic and creative earlier years; these problems emerge along with routine.
\par 
\par Disability {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Alliance{\*\xmlclose} was a more difficult group to manage, partly jus
t because they employed disabled people who had very diverse problems. Gender and generational differences. Also, unfortunate tendency for societies to be chaired by well-meaning retired admirals with no relevant skills. You might be able to run a battles
hip, but running the Spastics Society is of a different order. Lords and ladies tend to clog up the management system. 250 institutional members, and some individual members. Unwieldy organisation to make democratic. 
\par 
\par Colin Low has chaired the Disability Alliance educational and research association. This is a parallel charity to the campaigning {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Alliance{\*\xmlclose}
. Patient, diplomatic, a bit long-winded. Himself disabled. Remarkable political achievement of others, notably blind David Blunkett and deaf Jack Ashley as MPs. Fred Reid, blind social historian, was secretary of National Federation for the Blind.
\par 
\par Lorna Reith is the current director of Disability Alliance, sorting out internal problems. Before her, Sally Witcher, substantially disabled, live wire. Quick, loquacious, but has had many management problems.
\par 
\par Being spouse of an MP? Has been 18 years with Jean, a great fortune. Feels more of an insider. It's not just a question of knowing what needs to be done, but of knowing how to do it, in a variety of particular places.
\par 
\par Many people in politics have no idea of how to be a good politician. MPs and councillors have no training. He has learnt the life an MP leads, demands on them, sacks of correspondence, meetings they are expected to attend. Can only succeed
 collaboratively. Parliamentarians treated too much as cannon fodder. There is an increasing role for spouses of MPs, especially if provide research assistance. Peter has attended lots of parliamentary meetings.
\par 
\par Matthew and Adam born in 1952 and 1953, Chr
istian in 1957, and Benjamin in 1962. Started with romantic aspirations of a family of six children. Mixed feelings about whether he did enough as a father. Danced in the street when Matthew was born. Matthew, and last two, born at home; Adam in maternity
 hospital, because they were moving house. Disliked the disparaging treatment then given to fathers. They were romantically egalitarian but accepted divided roles. Remembers taking Matthew out in a pushchair in first year, when they were living in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Westminster{\*\xmlclose}
. Then moved into a working class terrace in Hampstead: warehouseman, fish and chip restauranteur, carpenter, builder, widows. Remembers very early morning walks with Matthew and Adam on the Heath. In the weeks, often home after bedtime, but at week
ends used to put them to bed, read and tell them stories which he made up. Loved that. Did it with all four sons. He now thinks he did not help enough with schoolwork; believed then that that should be left to the teachers. Did not want them to have too p
rivileged a start in life.
\par 
\par Great admiration for the simple living of men like Herbert Morrison and especially of George Lansbury. Peter came to socialism partly through the collective experience of the war.
\par 
\par Weekends a pleasure. Very sociable: in the stree
t itself, and also local girls who came in to help with the children, playing little mothers. Ruth helped care for a very sick neighbour. Ruth's mother also sometimes helped - more than Peter's. Ruth had a big kin network, so sometimes a big wedding.

\par 
\par Both
 were then physically fit. Aimed for a good balanced life, work on one side, home activities on the other, painting, carpentry, cooking - Peter did all those. Also often took the children to school. Affectionate, even riotous family life. Playing games in
 the alley and running on Parliament Hill Fields. Peter was running cross-country himself until sons in late teens. Holidays in Aldeburgh, and in Marghanita Laski's {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Somerset{\*\xmlclose}
 house with overgrown garden which they would clear. Entertained a lot at home: family, local friends like the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dickinsons{\*\xmlclose}
 (he was a doctor), professional friends; 1950s-60s especially Benns, Crossmans, Shores; and Brian Abel-Smith; LSE friends like Norman McKenzie. Semi-formal dinner parties. With just Ruth, occasional dinners out, or concerts at Festival Hall.
\par 
\par Social mixture in the neighbourhood not only of classes but also ethnic. Took up various cases. Woman who did washing put them in touch with Irish network in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Camden{\*\xmlclose}
 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Man with club foot who sold newspap
ers by Hampstead tube; tried to help when he and his mother were both seriously ill: inadequacy of the local social services for this couple. Another local man found dead in appalling circumstances, because so isolated. Getting neighbours into their house
 for a performances by his sons of song and dance.
\par 
\par In a way a realisation of the extended family neighbourhood he had researched in Bethnal Green. But it did not always work. He was unable to help his own depressed mother enough at that time.
\par 
\par Remembers visiting his mother in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Belsize Crescent{\*\xmlclose}
, finding her with a half-eaten meal in an alcoholic stupor. She was living with an alcoholic fallen toff. Peter was embarrassed by her. She was squeezed out by the other grandmother.
\par 
\par Once tried to combine camping with Ruth and the boys with attending the International Sociological Association Congress held in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Geneva{\*\xmlclose}
. Remembers Christian aged two and a half dancing wildly at the congress party. But it was wet too.
\par 
\par {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} changed his domestic life drastically. They decided, partly because the two eldest boys were starting at comprehensive schools, that Ruth and the boys would stay in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}London{\*\xmlclose}. Also because his grandmother had come to live with them: for the last ten years of her life, until 1970, with her daily Guinness, loving and loved by the children, a rock in the family, as she had been in Peter's early life. 

\par 
\par So Peter commuted for years, driving up to Colchester on Sunday night or Monday morning, and usually returning on Thursday; Friday was often a CPAG day in London. With being away four days, and also more and more campaigning, Peter became less of a family
 man.
\par 
\par Miserable life first in damp cold rented house in Wivenhoe, and then in lodgings in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose} with authoritarian landlady. Evenings, unless sometimes dinner with colleagues, ate on the cheap.
\par 
\par Began to diverge in his relationship with Ruth. She
 was not so interested in academic life. Finally broke up 1974. The previous year she had gone round the world in a Land Rover with Benjamin. Peter wanted her to publish her letters home as a travel autobiography, but in her distress she tore them up.

\par 
\par Bec
ause of their separation, they had both looked elsewhere for solace. In 1972 Peter met Joy Skegg, who had come to economics and researched on smoking, introduced by Tony Atkinson. Ruth was now very much involved with design and the children were reaching 
m
aturity. Ruth perhaps more cosmopolitan. Strong points of their 25 years marriage early romance, and the sons, and security and fulfilment of family life. Gave him a base which helped to make up for handicaps from his own origins. But had met very young. 
Marriage may be good for one time, without needing to last forever. 
\par 
\par The 1970s were the most unhappy period of his personal life, apart from the glorious happiness of Lucy's birth. Growing apart from both Ruth and the boys. Difficult anyway with four of di
fferent ages, because you need to do things separately with each. Tried to get to special school occasions. Thinks the boys blamed him for the separation. Ruth was trying to keep the house as a base. The boys scarcely ever came to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. On visits to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}, he tried to see his mother and one son each time. Nowhere to sleep in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London
{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par Now that Ruth has moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}, it is easier for him to be in contact with his sons. And Matthew is in a more familial phase with his second wife
. But numbers a problem: Jean and he have seven children and six grandsons between them, and she has a sister with two daughters and a father.
\par 
\par Ruth stayed on until recently in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose}. Had partners but never remarried. Helped run a restaurant. They don't exchange information themselves, and the sons don't talk much about her. 
\par 
\par After leaving the lodgings in Colchester Peter shared with Joy Skegg and two others, one a student, in a house by the station in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. He married Joy and Luc
y was born in 1976, and they moved to a small red brick farm cottage in Bures. A quiet registry wedding, with just the Sinfields.
\par 
\par Having Lucy was wonderful, like a second chance of being a father. First four years of her life they shared responsibility equally. Weekends each would take one day of childcare, one of work. Took her to nursery and fetched her back.
\par 
\par Maybe it was too early after the break with Ruth to commit himself to another family. Good things: he was able to feel more responsible, and Joy w
as more of a professional equal, understanding his worklife. But thinks he was almost deliberately blind to failings in the relationship, and when it ended suddenly felt a great relief at the end of pretence. Although many people could not understand how 
h
e could leave a wife with a young child. Cooked more than Joy did. Both loved having their child, but had not come to terms with who each other was. Peter was still coping with his break up, and the difficulty of keeping in touch with his sons. And still 
separated from his father, until later through Jean he got to know him. Joy had problems with her family too, which he thought mistakenly he could help her overcome. The new marriage was a consolation in a bad time.
\par 
\par Meeting Jean was the first time he had e
xperienced real love. An unrivalled period of ecstasy. Tarnished by the agony of being cut off from Lucy, with access only through a stiff and uncomprehending welfare officer. Eventually able to have her for weekends. Jean very understanding, making her c
l
othes, even though they would disappear when taken home. Lucy has survived, learning to keep her parents in two distinct compartments. Peter's distress when she was sent to a private school, against his principles, but Lucy herself decided to leave it. No
w know each other extremely well. She read art history at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose} and now has a job in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Westminster{\*\xmlclose}. Meet once or twice a week which is wonderful.

\par 
\par Saw much less of the boys, partly because of conflicting demands, but also because two were in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose} with their mother and not keen to see him, and for a while Ben was in remote 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}. Jean and he have now bought a cottage half an hour from where Ben lives. Ruth is also in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}. Joy is in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kentish{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Finds it now easier to talk over the phone to Joy than to Ruth.
\par 
\par Met Jean at the September 1980 Labour Party conference, at a lunch given by Tony Benn. Love at first sight: next day, coffee, and then the Labour Party Organisers' Dance.
\par 
\par Jean had been Women's Organiser and then became Regional Organiser for the South-West. Lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}
. Peter swept off his feet. Her father a leather glovemakers trade union organiser in Yeovil. Jean left school at 16. Her mother died young so Jean looked after her father
 and younger sister. Later she had a job in the Inland Revenue, married and had two children. Her husband had a hang-gliding accident and was paralysed from the waist, and they separated, so she was a lone parent. Very domesticated, with high skills in co
oking and needlework. Met her in September, and after Christmas he left Joy and went to live with Jean in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}. Commuted to Essex, until he was able to move to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Bristol{\*\xmlclose}. Got married in 1985. Jean has learned the hard way. Good at family as well 
as professional planning, and good at narratives. Very retentive memory. Daughter a doctor and son a teacher. Subsequently has read law at LSE. Elected MP for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}
 East in 1992. Can get to people of different levels, because from a working class background but a professional. And cares as much about their cleaner as about David Blunkett. 
\par 
\par Finds that aspect of her humanity stunningly attractive. Never thought he could get on so well with a woman. Peter can ea
sily feel guilt, and knows he is also obstinate, but there is an exceptional ease about their relationship. They share domestic tasks. Peter does nearly all the shopping. Life split between {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}, where he drives her around: terraced
 house in Peckham; and the Irish cottage. Share the gardening, Peter vegetables and Jean flowers. Jean is a very good washerwoman and proud to be the granddaughter of an Irish washerwoman. She is better with her hands, mending electrics etc. Peter tries c
arpentry.
\par 
\par Getting to know her children; David was 12 and Sarah 14. David was into zips and kept worms under his bed. Buying treats for them at the supermarket. It has been easier because Jean has good relations with her ex-husband. Peter was marginal espec
ially to Sarah. Only with David had any disciplinary role, and that very diffidently. Thinks David may have resented his intrusion on his closeness with his mother, but later played tennis and cricket together. Also playing together with the dog.
\par 
\par Moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} 1981-4 in Georgian terrace house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}St Paul{\*\xmlclose}
's area, which proved too dangerous: burgled three times, and Jean and Sarah were frightened to go out and Peter was mugged. 1984-7 in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}, while Jean worked briefly at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Walworth Road{\*\xmlclose}
 and then became a law student. Since 1987 in the country in Avening Green, in a former farm labourer's cottage. Their gardening help tells them about the past, when he lived there, and remote cottages like these were for the rural underclass.
\par 
\par Glad that he did his work on ageing when he was young.
\par 
\par Now at 70 he has learning what the experience of ageing is like. But it is different for different generations. Did not think about the possibility of dying before his fifties. Having a wife 14 years younger in
 some ways keeps ageing at bay, but he is worried that he may not be active enough for her.
\par 
\par Retired in 1993, but immediately re-employed by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} for another four years as emeritus professor. Now a visiting professor at LSE. So retirement does not 
really apply to him. Thinks that forcing people to retire simply because of their age is damaging to society. Has sometimes thought of taking up painting, or writing fiction, but is still doing things similar to those previously. Hopes to visit 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose} next year. Would like to write two more worthwhile books.
\par 
\par The best thing in his life: meeting with Jean. Also births of children. The worst things, losing mother and father; and the holocaust.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11749578 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16526652\charrsid1866470 
